@Jani__Gee If you have #ADHD please read my thread on why these clear containers are AMAZING for #ActuallyADHD people! 💙 https://t.co/J3CeyXhkxO

But when people struggle to do things the way most other people do it, they can start to feel like there is something wrong with them. 😔

Figuring out your own way of doing things that works best for you is SOOOO IMPORTANT.

Please don't make fun of what you don't understand. 💙

With clear containers and labels, I always will be able to see exactly what I have and how much I have of it. And seeing it like this on a regular basis, commits it to memory because the visual stays in my mind!

I cannot begin to tell you how much food I've had to throw out because of this or how many times I ran out of something I really needed because I just didn't know how much I already had.

This also means lots of money gets wasted. This isn't okay when you're already poor.

It's a very common occurance for people with ADHD, to literally forget that we have groceries because we can't see them.

So what ends up happening is food keeps getting wasted bc it expires, we don't know when we are running out of something or we have plenty & don't need more.

People with ADHD struggle with object permanence. It's what makes you know that something exists, even if you can't see it there.

For myself and many other people with ADHD, if it's out of sight, it's literally out of mind.

No, I will boo him because... Clear containers work BRILLIANTLY for people with ADHD!!!

I'll never know what would have happened if I wasn't teased for gaining weight, over eating and skipping meals. I'll never know what would have happened if I was instead treated like my health is more important than the size of my body.

Nowadays I have a much healthier relationship with food and my body. It took ALOT of hard work but I did it and I am still doing it. Im healthier now than ever and it's great!

But I still grieve the life I imagine I could have had if my ADHD had been diagnosed & treated earlier.

It sounds so ridiculous. But not eating for an entire made sense to me, but my body looking thinner did not. I was so used to skipping meals and still being fat. So when I started RAPIDLY losing weight, I got scared.

I had an extremely unhealthy relationship with food for YEARS. So much so, when I first started my ADHD meds and the side effects made me stop eating for multiple days at a time, I wasn't the least bit concerned. I wasn't concerned until I started to look different.

Whenever family members made awful fatphobic jokes about me or gave me fatphobic backhanded comiments, they were telling me I need to stop being fat, but they NEVER thought to ask *WHY* am I gaining so much weight and they damn sure never thought to ask how I felt about it.

I am slightly freaking out.... I am wearing size 4 jeans and I haven't been this small since I was like 15 years old.
